node.text:
Average duration of a human blink: 0.25 seconds.

A lot can happen in the blink of an eye.

Across the universe 15,000 stars will be born and 300 star will explode. 
15,000,000 rogue planets will form. 

The sun will burn 175,000,000 tons of hydrogen and produce 96,100,000,000,000,00,000,000,000 joules of energy.

30 black holes will be born. 

The universe will expand by 527,250 kilometers. 

Our galaxy will travel 250 kilometers and grow by 125 meters. 

The Andromeda galaxy will get 27 kilometers closer and light will travel 74,948 kilometers. 

Approximate number of blinks in a human lifetime: 650,000,000. 

Think next time you blink.

 🌌 My Pages @TheOurDeepSpace & @TheOurEpicNature 🔭

Do you love Universe ❤

Are you ready to explore Space 🔭 @TheOurSpace

Image credit: @melodysheep_

node.title: In the Blink of an Eye: Space in an Instant

node.text:
"Summer show" 🌕 

A week ago, the two biggest planets Jupiter and Saturn had an appointment with the full blue moon (the 2nd full moon of the same month) for an unprecedented spectacle. I wanted to mark the occasion with this composition. Sizes and distances are not to scale, and have been intentionally accentuated for a more artistic effect. 🔭 My Pages @TheOurEpicNature & @TheOurDeepSpace 

Do you love Moon ❤

Journey to the center of the Galaxy (Sagittarius A black hole) 🌌 🕳 🔭 @TheOurDeepSpace @TheOurEpicNature 

Sagittarius A* is a bright and very compact astronomical radio source at the Galactic Center of the Milky Way. It is located near the border of the constellations Sagittarius and Scorpius, about 5.6° south of the ecliptic.

node.text:
The Butterfly Nebula. 🌌 @TheOurDeepSpace @TheOurEpicNature 🔭

One of the most complex nebulae structures we’ve ever observed; The Butterfly Nebula. Also known as the bug nebula. Comment some other names that could work if you have better ideas! It’s classified as a bipolar planetary nebula and it’s located 3,400 light years asay from us with a radius of about 2 light years. It was formed by a dying star with 5 times the mass of our Sun. 🔭 

Do you love Butterfly Nebula ❤

node.text:
How to Write "Neutron Stars" in Your Language. 🖤 There's Now Strong Evidence That an Exotic Type of Matter Exists Inside Neutron Stars.

A research group has found strong evidence for the presence of exotic quark matter inside the cores of the largest neutron stars in existence. The conclusion was reached by combining recent results from theoretical particle and nuclear physics to measurements of gravitational waves from neutron star collisions. 

Do you love Neutron Stars ❤

Are you ready to explore Space 🔭 @TheOurSpace

node.text:
Quasars give off huge amounts of energy. They can be a trillion times brighter than the Sun! Astronomers think that quasars are located in galaxies which have black holes at their centers. The black holes may provide quasars with their energy. Quasars are so bright that they drown out the light from all other stars in the same galaxy. The word quasar is short for quasi-stellar radio source. Quasars give off radio waves, X-rays, gamma-rays, ultraviolet rays, and visible light. Most of them are larger than our solar system.

Do you love Quasar ❤

Are you ready to explore Space 🔭 @TheOurSpace

node.text:
On Jan. 5, 2020, astrophysicists heard a chirp from a distant part of the cosmos, some 900 million light-years away.

On Jan. 5, 2020, astrophysicists heard a chirp from a distant part of the cosmos, some 900 million light-years away.

After careful analysis, the two signals have been identified as emanating from extreme, never-before-seen events in deep space: the collision between a black hole and a neutron star.

The two newly described events are named GW200105 and GW200115, for the dates they were discovered, and provide the first definitive evidence of an elusive merger. 🕳 🌌 My Pages @TheOurDeepSpace & @TheOurEpicNature 🔭

Do you love Black Holes 🕳

Are you ready to explore Space 🔭 @TheOurSpace

node.text:
Using one of the largest telescopes in the world ("Very Large Telescope", or "VLT"), astronomers found a star that "dances" around a black hole in the Milky Way, forming the pattern of a rosette.
 ㅤ
 The movement of the S2 star around the supermassive black hole Sagittarius A * at the center of the Milky Way proved that Albert Einstein was right about gravity once again.  The images prove predictions made by Einstein in his General Theory of Relativity, published in 1915, the foundation of modern physics.
 ㅤ
 The S2 star surrounds the supermassive black hole in the center of the Milky Way once every 16 years.  For almost 30 years, astronomers have been observing it to accurately trace its circular orbit.
 ㅤ
 This rosette-shaped orbit occurs thanks to the “amplification” of an effect due to the enormous gravity of the black hole.  This effect, known as Schwarzchild's precession, had never been measured before in a star orbiting a supermassive black hole.

The universe is a gigantic art-generating system, don't you agree? 🕳 🌌 My Pages @TheOurDeepSpace & @TheOurEpicNature 🔭

Monster Black Holes Are About to Collide 🕳 🌌 My Pages @TheOurDeepSpace & @TheOurEpicNature 🔭

A rare trio of supermassive black holes has been caught in the act of coming together. 🔭

Three of the light-gobbling monsters nuzzle shoulder to shoulder in SDSS J084905.51+111447.2, a system of three merging galaxies about 1 billion light-years from Earth, a new study reports. "We were only looking for pairs of black holes at the time, and yet, through our selection technique, we stumbled upon this amazing system," lead author Ryan Pfeifle, of George Mason University in Virginia, said in a statement. "This is the strongest evidence yet found for such a triple system of actively feeding supermassive black holes." Making the epic find wasn't easy; it took observations by multiple instruments and help from lots of citizen scientists. 🔭
